# Add Sensor — AI Agent Workflow

> Generated for <%= robot.name %>. Use: "Help me add a new sensor to <%= robot.name %>"

## Pre-flight Checks

1. Read `robot.hardware.yaml` — understand current hardware layout
2. Read `packages/knowledge/sensors/` — check if sensor already in knowledge base
3. Read `firmware/inc/can_config.h` — check available CAN IDs (if using CAN bus)

## Steps

1. **Add sensor to `robot.hardware.yaml`**
   ```yaml
   sensors:
     - name: "<sensor_name>"
       model: "<knowledge-base-id>"
       interface: "<UART|SPI|I2C|USB|CAN|GPIO>"
       port: "<port>"
   ```

2. **If sensor not in knowledge base**, create `packages/knowledge/sensors/<new_sensor>.yaml` following the template in `CONTRIBUTING.md`

3. **Re-run generation**
   ```bash
   npx tsx scripts/generate.ts
   ```

4. **Verify changes**
   - `firmware/` — new sensor initialization added
   - `urdf/` — sensor mount link added (if mount configured)
   - `ros2_ws/` — sensor driver node added to launch
   - `CLAUDE.md` — updated with new hardware entry

## Safety

- `@ai-lock`: Never change existing motor CAN IDs to accommodate a new sensor
- `@ai-critical`: Verify the selected port doesn't conflict with existing peripherals
- `@ai-extend`: Add custom sensor processing code in the generated driver template

## Example

> "Add a VL53L5CX ToF sensor on I2C bus 1"

Agent should:
1. Confirm sensor exists in knowledge base (or create entry)
2. Add to `robot.hardware.yaml` sensors list
3. Run generation
4. Verify no peripheral conflicts
